            <section class="prose">
              <h2>Thin Lens Equation: Definition and Formula</h2>
              <p>
                The thin lens equation relates the focal length of a lens to the
                distances of the object and image from the lens. It is a
                cornerstone of geometric optics and is widely used in physics,
                engineering, photography, and vision science.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Thin lens equation</p>
                <p>\[ \frac{1}{f} = \frac{1}{d_o} + \frac{1}{d_i} \]</p>
                <ul class="text-sm mt-2">
                  <li>\(f\) = focal length of the lens</li>
                  <li>
                    \(d_o\) = object distance (distance from object to lens)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    \(d_i\) = image distance (distance from image to lens)
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <p>
                The linear magnification \(m\) produced by the lens is given by:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Magnification</p>
                <p>\[ m = -\frac{d_i}{d_o} \]</p>
                <ul class="text-sm mt-2">
                  <li>
                    \(|m| &gt; 1\): image is larger than the object (magnified)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    \(|m| &lt; 1\): image is smaller than the object (reduced)
                  </li>
                  <li>\(m &lt; 0\): image is inverted</li>
                  <li>\(m &gt; 0\): image is upright</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h2>Sign Conventions Used in This Calculator</h2>
              <p>
                There are several sign conventions in optics (e.g.,
                real-is-positive, Gaussian, Cartesian). This calculator uses a
                common <strong>real-is-positive convention</strong>:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Object distance \(d_o\)</strong>: positive for real
                  objects (on the incoming-light side of the lens).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Image distance \(d_i\)</strong>:
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      \(d_i &gt; 0\): real image, on the opposite side of the
                      lens from the object.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      \(d_i &lt; 0\): virtual image, on the same side as the
                      object.
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Focal length \(f\)</strong>:
                  <ul>
                    <li>\(f &gt; 0\): converging (convex) lens.</li>
                    <li>\(f &lt; 0\): diverging (concave) lens.</li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                In the interface, you normally enter
                <strong>positive distances</strong> for real objects and images.
                The lens type (converging or diverging) determines the sign of
                \(f\). The calculator then computes \(d_i\) (which may be
                positive or negative) and interprets the result for you.
              </p>

              <h2>How to Use the Thin Lens Equation Calculator</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Choose what to solve for.</strong>
                  Select whether you want to compute the focal length \(f\),
                  object distance \(d_o\), or image distance \(d_i\).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Enter the known distances.</strong>
                  Provide the other two distances. For example, to solve for
                  \(d_i\), enter \(f\) and \(d_o\).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Select lens type and units.</strong>
                  Choose converging or diverging lens and your preferred
                  distance units (mm, cm, or m).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Click “Calculate”.</strong>
                  The tool returns:
                  <ul>
                    <li>the unknown distance,</li>
                    <li>magnification \(m\),</li>
                    <li>whether the image is real or virtual,</li>
                    <li>whether it is upright or inverted,</li>
                    <li>whether it is magnified or reduced,</li>
                    <li>a simple ray-diagram style visualization.</li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Rearranging the Thin Lens Equation</h2>
              <p>
                You can solve the thin lens equation for any of the three
                distances.
              </p>

              <h3>Solve for image distance \(d_i\)</h3>
              <p>
                Starting from \(\frac{1}{f} = \frac{1}{d_o} + \frac{1}{d_i}\):
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \[ \frac{1}{d_i} = \frac{1}{f} - \frac{1}{d_o} \] \[ d_i =
                \frac{1}{\dfrac{1}{f} - \dfrac{1}{d_o}} \]
              </div>

              <h3>Solve for object distance \(d_o\)</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \[ \frac{1}{d_o} = \frac{1}{f} - \frac{1}{d_i} \] \[ d_o =
                \frac{1}{\dfrac{1}{f} - \dfrac{1}{d_i}} \]
              </div>

              <h3>Solve for focal length \(f\)</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \[ \frac{1}{f} = \frac{1}{d_o} + \frac{1}{d_i} \] \[ f =
                \frac{1}{\dfrac{1}{d_o} + \dfrac{1}{d_i}} \]
              </div>

              <h2>Worked Examples</h2>

              <h3>1. Converging lens forming a real, inverted image</h3>
              <p>
                Suppose a converging lens has focal length \(f = 10\
                \text{cm}\), and an object is placed at \(d_o = 30\ \text{cm}\).
              </p>
              <p>Compute the image distance:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \[ \frac{1}{d_i} = \frac{1}{f} - \frac{1}{d_o} = \frac{1}{10} -
                \frac{1}{30} = \frac{3 - 1}{30} = \frac{2}{30} = \frac{1}{15} \]
                \[ d_i = 15\ \text{cm} \] \[ m = -\frac{d_i}{d_o} =
                -\frac{15}{30} = -0.5 \]
              </div>
              <p>
                Interpretation: the image is <strong>real</strong> (\(d_i &gt;
                0\)), <strong>inverted</strong> (\(m &lt; 0\)), and
                <strong>reduced</strong> in size (\(|m| = 0.5\)).
              </p>

              <h3>2. Converging lens forming a virtual, upright image</h3>
              <p>
                Now place the object closer to the same lens: \(f = 10\
                \text{cm}\), \(d_o = 5\ \text{cm}\) (inside the focal length).
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \[ \frac{1}{d_i} = \frac{1}{10} - \frac{1}{5} = \frac{1 - 2}{10}
                = -\frac{1}{10} \] \[ d_i = -10\ \text{cm} \] \[ m =
                -\frac{d_i}{d_o} = -\frac{-10}{5} = 2 \]
              </div>
              <p>
                Interpretation: the image is <strong>virtual</strong> (\(d_i
                &lt; 0\)), <strong>upright</strong> (\(m &gt; 0\)), and
                <strong>magnified</strong> (\(|m| = 2\)).
              </p>

              <h3>3. Diverging lens</h3>
              <p>
                For a diverging lens with focal length \(f = -15\ \text{cm}\)
                and an object at \(d_o = 30\ \text{cm}\):
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \[ \frac{1}{d_i} = \frac{1}{f} - \frac{1}{d_o} = \frac{1}{-15} -
                \frac{1}{30} = -\frac{2}{30} - \frac{1}{30} = -\frac{3}{30} =
                -\frac{1}{10} \] \[ d_i = -10\ \text{cm} \] \[ m =
                -\frac{d_i}{d_o} = -\frac{-10}{30} = \frac{1}{3} \]
              </div>
              <p>
                The image is <strong>virtual</strong>, <strong>upright</strong>,
                and <strong>reduced</strong>, as expected for a diverging lens
                with a real object.
              </p>

              <h2>Common Use Cases</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Physics labs:</strong> determining the focal length of
                  an unknown lens from measured object and image distances.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Photography:</strong> relating subject distance, focal
                  length, and image distance (sensor position) in camera design.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Vision science:</strong> modeling corrective lenses
                  and simple optical instruments.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>MCAT and exam prep:</strong> quickly classifying
                  images (real/virtual, inverted/upright, magnified/reduced)
                  without memorizing every case.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>What is the thin lens equation?</h3>
              <p>
                The thin lens equation is \(\frac{1}{f} = \frac{1}{d_o} +
                \frac{1}{d_i}\). It assumes the lens thickness is negligible
                compared with the object and image distances, so refraction can
                be treated as occurring at a single plane.
              </p>

              <h3>How do I know if the image is real or virtual?</h3>
              <p>Using the sign convention in this calculator:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  \(d_i &gt; 0\): image is <strong>real</strong>, on the
                  opposite side of the lens from the object.
                </li>
                <li>
                  \(d_i &lt; 0\): image is <strong>virtual</strong>, on the same
                  side as the object.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>What do positive and negative focal lengths mean?</h3>
              <p>
                A positive focal length corresponds to a
                <strong>converging (convex)</strong> lens, which can form real
                images of real objects. A negative focal length corresponds to a
                <strong>diverging (concave)</strong> lens, which forms only
                virtual images for real objects.
              </p>

              <h3>How is magnification related to the thin lens equation?</h3>
              <p>
                Once you know \(d_o\) and \(d_i\), the magnification is \(m =
                -d_i/d_o\). The sign and magnitude of \(m\) tell you whether the
                image is inverted or upright and whether it is larger or smaller
                than the object.
              </p>

              <h3>When is the thin lens approximation valid?</h3>
              <p>The approximation is valid when:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  the lens thickness is small compared with \(d_o\) and \(d_i\),
                  and
                </li>
                <li>
                  rays make small angles with the optical axis (paraxial
                  approximation).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For thick lenses, strongly curved lenses, or wide-angle systems,
                more advanced models (e.g., thick lens or matrix optics) are
                needed.
              </p>
